<div id="review_105610480" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/105610480" />
    <a title="Michelle Cristiani" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1135369-michelle-cristiani"><img alt="Michelle Cristiani" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1246662649p2/1135369.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/105610480?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle Cristiani" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle Cristiani" href="/user/show/1135369-michelle-cristiani">Michelle Cristiani</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1135369-michelle-cristiani?shelf=memoirs">memoirs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1135369-michelle-cristiani?shelf=cooking-and-food">cooking-and-food</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer105610480" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8450749198357831683">This is a story of pie along American backroads, by a food writer who was moving from West to East coast and wanted to make her road trip more interesting. It tells stories of small towns, their pies, and the bakers who make them (usually elderly women). She wonders if the art of pie-making is dying out because of our inability to slow down, and our unwillingness to learn from the past (i.e., our grandmothers). <br/><br/>Because Le Draoulec is already a food critic and author, she has no problem panning s</span>
  <span id="freeText8450749198357831683" style="display:none">This is a story of pie along American backroads, by a food writer who was moving from West to East coast and wanted to make her road trip more interesting. It tells stories of small towns, their pies, and the bakers who make them (usually elderly women). She wonders if the art of pie-making is dying out because of our inability to slow down, and our unwillingness to learn from the past (i.e., our grandmothers). <br /><br />Because Le Draoulec is already a food critic and author, she has no problem panning some of the pies, or even describing the people she meets in an honest, near-critical tone. The idea of 'dumpster pie' gave me a chuckle. What's more, she has no problem with injecting herself into social situations in the name of pie: including squeezing into a diner booth with a snuggling couple, asking shopowners to open when the store is closed, crashing a funeral, and crashing a Thanksgiving dinner with PEOPLE SHE'D NEVER MET. I guess in her mind the end (pie story) justified the means (rudeness), but maybe in some situations, the cost was a little high. Though I guess no shy person would just set out on a road trip about pie without the faintest idea of where to look. She pretty much stumbled upon every pie story by asking the locals. That haphazard style made some of the book tiresome, and also made me wonder how much she missed by not being more systematic. But, what she recorded is an important part of American history and lore. And the recipes are outstanding - though I would have preferred a recipe index.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8450749198357831683" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

